The paper discusses a novel architecture for running convolutional neural nets (CNNs) efficiently on FPGAs, particularly in the area of image classification. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition (cs.CV) sub-category. Additionally, the paper focuses on maximizing data reuse and minimizing external memory bandwidth, which suggests that it may also belong to the Architecture (cs.AR) and Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-categories. The paper also discusses the use of the Winograd transform to boost performance, which suggests that it may belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the use of the Intel Arria 10 device, which suggests that it may also belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category.
